## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### The beat is the anchor

The `transport/tempo` verb sets the pace — beats per minute. Every `note/place-at` call asks for a beat position: the *when*. The engine schedules sound at that position in musical time, regardless of the tempo.

```scheme
;; A single note, placed on beat 1
(transport/tempo 90)
(note/place-at 1 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: A staff with a single quarter note on C4, a tempo marking ♩ = 90 above. The note-sprite bops at 90 BPM.]`

<!-- BUILD: render staff with one quarter note; tempo annotation; note-sprite animates at 90 BPM -->

```scheme
;; The same note, faster tempo
(transport/tempo 160)
(note/place-at 1 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
```

The *duration* symbol `'quarter` remains — but at 160 BPM, the note sounds and finishes in less wall-clock time. The beat is the anchor; tempo stretches or compresses the clock.

---


### Rests have duration too

A rest is not silence — it is *measured* silence, as much a part of the rhythm as a sounding note.

```scheme
;; Two notes separated by a quarter rest
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/place-at 1 'D4 'quarter 0.75)
;; rest occupies beat 2
(note/place-at 3 'D4 'quarter 0.75)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff with two quarter notes on D4, beats 1 and 3, a quarter rest glyph on beat 2.]`

<!-- BUILD: render staff with two notes + rest glyph; rest-sprite idles at quarter-rest motion rate (same as quarter note) -->

```scheme
;; A phrase with rests shaping the rhythm
(transport/tempo 110)
(note/place-at 1 'E4 'eighth 0.8)
(note/place-at 1.5 'E4 'eighth 0.8)
;; eighth rest at beat 2
(note/place-at 2.5 'G4 'eighth 0.8)
(note/place-at 3 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff showing the eighth-eighth-rest-eighth-quarter pattern. Rest glyph at beat 2, eighth-rest size.]`

<!-- BUILD: render staff; eighth-rest sprite at beat 2 -->

---


### Time signatures: the measure's shape

A time signature tells you how many beats fill one measure, and what note-value counts as one beat. `4/4` means four quarter-note beats per measure. `3/4` means three. `2/4` means two.

```scheme
;; A 3/4 phrase (waltz time)
(transport/tempo 120)
(note/place-at 1 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 2 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 3 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
;; measure 2
(note/place-at 4 'E4 'half 0.75)
(note/place-at 6 'C4 'quarter 0.75)
```

`[VISUAL: Two measures in 3/4 time. First measure: three quarter notes (C–E–G). Second measure: half note E (beats 1–2), quarter note C (beat 3). Time signature 3/4 at the start of the staff.]`

<!-- BUILD: render two-measure staff with 3/4 time signature glyph; barline between measures -->

The barline divides measures. The time signature sets the expectation: in `3/4`, beat 1 of each measure is the *downbeat* — the strongest accent.

```scheme
;; A 2/4 march fragment
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/place-at 1 'G3 'quarter 0.9)
(note/place-at 2 'G3 'quarter 0.9)
(note/place-at 3 'D4 'quarter 0.85)
(note/place-at 4 'D4 'quarter 0.85)
```

`[VISUAL: Two measures in 2/4 time. Each measure has two quarter notes. Time signature 2/4 at the start.]`

<!-- BUILD: render 2/4 time signature glyph + two-measure staff -->

---


### Syncopation: accenting the weak beat

Syncopation moves emphasis *off* the downbeat, creating rhythmic surprise.

```scheme
;; A syncopated pattern in 4/4
(transport/tempo 105)
(note/place-at 1 'C4 'eighth 0.6)
(note/place-at 1.5 'D4 'eighth 0.9)  ;; accent on the offbeat
(note/place-at 2 'E4 'eighth 0.6)
(note/place-at 2.5 'F4 'eighth 0.9)
(note/place-at 3 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 4 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff in 4/4. Eighth notes on beats 1, 1.5, 2, 2.5; quarter notes on beats 3 and 4. Accent marks (>) over the offbeat notes at 1.5 and 2.5.]`

<!-- BUILD: render staff with accent marks; note-sprites on offbeats glow/bob more strongly -->

The velocity on the offbeats (0.9) is higher than the on-beats (0.6), shifting the felt pulse.

```scheme
;; A longer syncopated groove
(transport/tempo 108)
(note/place-at 1 'A3 'eighth 0.5)
(note/place-at 1.5 'A3 'eighth 0.85)
(note/place-at 2.5 'C4 'eighth 0.85)
(note/place-at 3 'A3 'eighth 0.5)
(note/place-at 3.5 'A3 'eighth 0.85)
(note/place-at 4.5 'E4 'eighth 0.9)
```

`[VISUAL: One measure in 4/4, syncopated eighths. Offbeat notes (1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 4.5) marked with accents.]`

<!-- BUILD: render one-measure staff, accent glyphs on offbeats -->

---


### Dotted rhythms: uneven subdivision

A dotted note is 1.5 times its base duration. A dotted quarter in `4/4` lasts 1.5 beats.

```scheme
;; Dotted quarter followed by eighth
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/place-at 1 'D4 'quarter 0.8)     ;; dotted would be 1.5 beats *[needs: GAP-1]*
(note/place-at 2.5 'E4 'eighth 0.8)
(note/place-at 3 'F4 'quarter 0.8)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — dotted durations are not yet in the engine. The example above uses a quarter + eighth separation to approximate the rhythm. When GAP-1 closes, write:

```scheme
;; Dotted quarter followed by eighth (once GAP-1 is closed)
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/place-at 1 'D4 'dotted-quarter 0.8)  ;; *[needs: GAP-1]*
(note/place-at 2.5 'E4 'eighth 0.8)
(note/place-at 3 'F4 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff with a dotted-quarter note (D4), an eighth note (E4), and a quarter note (F4). The dot is visible next to the first note-head.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, render dotted-quarter glyph; note-sprite has visible dot ornament -->

---


### Triplets: dividing the beat into three

A triplet fits three notes into the space of two. An eighth-note triplet in `4/4` divides one quarter beat into three equal parts.

```scheme
;; Eighth-note triplet spanning one beat (approximated with manual placement)
(transport/tempo 90)
(note/place-at 1 'C4 'eighth 0.75)       ;; first of triplet
(note/place-at 1.333 'D4 'eighth 0.75)   ;; second *[needs: GAP-1]*
(note/place-at 1.667 'E4 'eighth 0.75)   ;; third
(note/place-at 2 'F4 'quarter 0.8)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — true triplet syntax is not yet in the engine. The example manually places notes at fractional beats (1, 1.333, 1.667) to approximate the triplet subdivision. When GAP-1 closes, the engine will accept `'triplet-eighth` and handle the math.

`[VISUAL: Staff showing three eighth notes grouped under a triplet bracket labeled \"3\". Then a quarter note. The triplet notes fit into one beat's time.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, render triplet bracket glyph; note-sprites grouped visually -->

---


### Changing tempo mid-phrase: ritardando and accelerando

`transport/tempo` can be called more than once. Changing it mid-phrase creates a ritardando (slowing) or accelerando (speeding up).

```scheme
;; A phrase that slows down
(transport/tempo 120)
(note/place-at 1 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 2 'A4 'quarter 0.8)

(transport/tempo 100)
(note/place-at 3 'B4 'quarter 0.8)

(transport/tempo 80)
(note/place-at 4 'C5 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff with four quarter notes. Tempo markings above: ♩ = 120 at beat 1, ♩ = 100 at beat 3, ♩ = 80 at beat 4. A \"rit.\" marking above beats 3–4.]`

<!-- BUILD: render staff with multiple tempo annotations; \"rit.\" text glyph -->

The tempo changes are *discrete* — each takes effect at the next scheduled note. For a *smooth* ritardando, you would need to change tempo continuously, which is not yet supported *[needs: GAP-1 extension for tempo curves]*.

```scheme
;; A phrase that speeds up
(transport/tempo 80)
(note/place-at 1 'C4 'quarter 0.8)

(transport/tempo 100)
(note/place-at 2 'D4 'quarter 0.8)

(transport/tempo 120)
(note/place-at 3 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 4 'F4 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff with four quarter notes. Tempo markings: ♩ = 80, then ♩ = 100, then ♩ = 120. An \"accel.\" marking.]`

<!-- BUILD: render staff with accel. text glyph -->

---


### Polymeter: two time signatures at once

Polymeter layers rhythms in different meters simultaneously. One voice in `3/4`, another in `4/4`.

```scheme
;; Voice 1 in 3/4 (high)
(transport/tempo 120)
(note/place-at 1 'E5 'quarter 0.7)
(note/place-at 2 'G5 'quarter 0.7)
(note/place-at 3 'E5 'quarter 0.7)
(note/place-at 4 'E5 'quarter 0.7)
(note/place-at 5 'G5 'quarter 0.7)
(note/place-at 6 'E5 'quarter 0.7)

;; Voice 2 in 4/4 (low)
(note/place-at 1 'C3 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 2 'C3 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 3 'C3 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 4 'C3 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 5 'C3 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 6 'C3 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Two staves stacked. Top staff in 3/4, bottom in 4/4. The measures align at beat 1, then diverge. Barlines for each staff appear at different beat positions. After 12 beats, both meters cycle back into phase.]`

<!-- BUILD: render two-staff system with independent time signatures and barlines -->

At beat 1, both voices align (downbeat). The `3/4` voice completes a measure every 3 beats; the `4/4` voice every 4 beats. They realign at beat 13 (the least common multiple of 3 and 4 is 12, so they meet again at beat 13, the start of the next cycle).

---


### A simple duple march (2/4)

```scheme
;; Left-right march pattern
(transport/tempo 110)
(define (march-step beat pitch)
  (note/place-at beat pitch 'quarter 0.85))

(march-step 1 'G3)
(march-step 2 'G3)
(march-step 3 'D4)
(march-step 4 'D4)
(march-step 5 'G3)
(march-step 6 'G3)
(march-step 7 'B3)
(march-step 8 'B3)
```

`[VISUAL: Four measures in 2/4. Two quarter notes per measure, alternating G3–G3, D4–D4, G3–G3, B3–B3. Strong downbeat accents on beats 1, 3, 5, 7.]`

<!-- BUILD: render four-measure 2/4 staff; downbeat note-sprites bob more strongly -->

---


### A simple triple meter (3/4 waltz)

```scheme
;; Waltz bass pattern: strong downbeat, two lighter beats
(transport/tempo 140)
(define (waltz-measure beat root)
  (note/place-at beat root 'quarter 0.9)
  (note/place-at (+ beat 1) root 'quarter 0.6)
  (note/place-at (+ beat 2) root 'quarter 0.6))

(waltz-measure 1 'C3)
(waltz-measure 4 'G3)
(waltz-measure 7 'C3)
```

`[VISUAL: Three measures in 3/4. Each measure has three quarter notes on the same pitch. The first note of each measure has an accent mark, the other two do not.]`

<!-- BUILD: render 3/4 waltz staff with accent marks on downbeats -->

