### Subdividing the beat: sixteenth notes

Sixteenth notes divide the quarter beat into four parts. In `4/4` at a moderate tempo, they are fast.

```scheme
;; A rapid sixteenth-note run
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/place-at 1 'C4 'sixteenth 0.75)
(note/place-at 1.25 'D4 'sixteenth 0.75)
(note/place-at 1.5 'E4 'sixteenth 0.75)
(note/place-at 1.75 'F4 'sixteenth 0.75)
(note/place-at 2 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff showing four sixteenth notes beamed together (C–D–E–F), followed by a quarter note (G). The beam connects all four sixteenths.]`

<!-- BUILD: render beamed sixteenth-note group; sixteenth note-sprites bob at fastest rate -->

```scheme
;; Alternating eighths and sixteenths
(transport/tempo 95)
(note/place-at 1 'E4 'eighth 0.8)
(note/place-at 1.5 'F4 'sixteenth 0.7)
(note/place-at 1.75 'G4 'sixteenth 0.7)
(note/place-at 2 'A4 'eighth 0.8)
(note/place-at 2.5 'G4 'eighth 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff with eighth, two sixteenths (beamed), eighth, eighth. Mixed beaming shows the subdivision clearly.]`

<!-- BUILD: render mixed eighth/sixteenth beaming -->

---


### Hemiola: shifting the accent pattern

A hemiola is a rhythmic trick: in `3/4` or `6/8`, you accent as if the meter were `2/4`, creating a temporary feeling of duple time.

```scheme
;; Three measures of 3/4, accented as two groups of three eighth notes
(transport/tempo 120)
(note/place-at 1 'D4 'eighth 0.9)
(note/place-at 1.5 'D4 'eighth 0.6)
(note/place-at 2 'D4 'eighth 0.6)

(note/place-at 2.5 'D4 'eighth 0.9)
(note/place-at 3 'D4 'eighth 0.6)
(note/place-at 3.5 'D4 'eighth 0.6)

(note/place-at 4 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: One measure of 3/4 with six eighth notes, grouped into two sets of three by accent marks (beats 1 and 2.5 accented). The final measure has a quarter note, returning to normal 3/4 feel.]`

<!-- BUILD: render hemiola staff with accent marks showing 2-against-3 grouping -->

The listener hears two groups of three eighths, not three groups of two — the hemiola.

---


### Swing rhythm: uneven eighths

Swing is a rhythmic feel where written eighth notes are played unevenly — the first eighth is longer, the second shorter, approximating a triplet subdivision.

```scheme
;; Approximating swing with manual placement (not true swing yet)
(transport/tempo 110)
(note/place-at 1 'C4 'eighth 0.8)
(note/place-at 1.667 'E4 'eighth 0.8)   ;; delayed second eighth *[needs: GAP-1]*
(note/place-at 2 'G4 'eighth 0.8)
(note/place-at 2.667 'E4 'eighth 0.8)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — true swing timing (a global \"swing feel\" parameter) is not yet in the engine. This example manually offsets the second eighth note of each beat to approximate the swing subdivision.

`[VISUAL: Staff with four eighth notes. A \"swing\" marking above. The note-spacing on the staff visually suggests uneven subdivision (long-short, long-short).]`

<!-- BUILD: when swing feel is added, render \"swing\" text glyph; note-sprites space unevenly -->

---


### Cross-rhythm: three against two

A cross-rhythm layers two conflicting subdivisions. Three notes in the time of two creates a `3:2` polyrhythm.

```scheme
;; Voice 1: quarter-note pulse (2 beats)
(transport/tempo 90)
(note/place-at 1 'C3 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 2 'C3 'quarter 0.8)

;; Voice 2: triplet subdivision (3 notes over the same 2 beats)
(note/place-at 1 'E4 'eighth 0.7)       ;; triplet eighths *[needs: GAP-1]*
(note/place-at 1.667 'G4 'eighth 0.7)
(note/place-at 2.333 'E4 'eighth 0.7)
```

`[VISUAL: Two staves. Bottom staff: two quarter notes (C3). Top staff: three eighth notes (E–G–E) with a triplet bracket, spanning the same two beats.]`

<!-- BUILD: render two-staff cross-rhythm; triplet bracket on top staff -->

---


### Changing meter mid-piece

```scheme
;; Two measures of 4/4, then switch to 3/4
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/place-at 1 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 2 'A4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 3 'B4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 4 'C5 'quarter 0.8)

;; measure 2 (still 4/4)
(note/place-at 5 'D5 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 6 'C5 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 7 'B4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 8 'A4 'quarter 0.8)

;; measure 3 (now 3/4)
(note/place-at 9 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 10 'A4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 11 'B4 'quarter 0.8)

;; measure 4 (still 3/4)
(note/place-at 12 'C5 'half 0.8)
(note/place-at 14 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Four measures. Time signature 4/4 at the start, changing to 3/4 at measure 3. Barlines show the different measure lengths.]`

<!-- BUILD: render multi-meter staff with time signature changes -->

---


### Metric modulation: the beat changes value

In a metric modulation, the tempo stays constant in terms of *a different subdivision*. For example, the old eighth note becomes the new quarter note.

```scheme
;; Before modulation: quarter = 120
(transport/tempo 120)
(note/place-at 1 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 2 'D4 'quarter 0.8)

;; After modulation: the old eighth becomes the new quarter
;; old eighth at 120 quarter-BPM = 240 eighth-BPM
;; new quarter = old eighth → new quarter-BPM = 240
(transport/tempo 240)
(note/place-at 3 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 4 'F4 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Two measures. First measure at ♩ = 120. Between measures, a metric modulation marking: ♪ = ♩ (old eighth equals new quarter). Second measure at ♩ = 240.]`

<!-- BUILD: render metric modulation symbol between staves -->

The music *feels* like it doubled in speed, but mathematically it's a clean modulation: the subdivision that was running at one rate is now the new beat.

---


### Additive meters: 5/8 and 7/8

Meters like `5/8` or `7/8` are *additive* — they group beats into unequal clusters (e.g., `5/8 = 2+3` or `3+2`).

```scheme
;; A 5/8 pattern grouped as 2+3
(transport/tempo 140)
(note/place-at 1 'D4 'eighth 0.85)       ;; group of 2
(note/place-at 1.5 'D4 'eighth 0.85)

(note/place-at 2 'E4 'eighth 0.75)       ;; group of 3
(note/place-at 2.5 'F4 'eighth 0.75)
(note/place-at 3 'E4 'eighth 0.75)
```

`[VISUAL: One measure in 5/8 time. Five eighth notes, with accent marks or beaming showing a 2+3 grouping.]`

<!-- BUILD: render 5/8 time signature; beaming shows 2+3 subdivision -->

```scheme
;; A 7/8 pattern grouped as 2+2+3
(transport/tempo 130)
(note/place-at 1 'A4 'eighth 0.8)
(note/place-at 1.5 'A4 'eighth 0.8)

(note/place-at 2 'B4 'eighth 0.8)
(note/place-at 2.5 'B4 'eighth 0.8)

(note/place-at 3 'C5 'eighth 0.75)
(note/place-at 3.5 'D5 'eighth 0.75)
(note/place-at 4 'C5 'eighth 0.75)
```

`[VISUAL: One measure in 7/8 time. Seven eighth notes, beamed/accented as 2+2+3.]`

<!-- BUILD: render 7/8 time signature with 2+2+3 beaming -->

