### A rhythm with tied notes (extending duration across a barline)

A tie connects two notes of the same pitch, adding their durations together. Ties are not yet in the engine *[needs: GAP-2]*, but you can manually extend duration.

```scheme
;; A note that lasts from beat 4 of measure 1 into beat 1 of measure 2
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/place-at 1 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 2 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 3 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 4 'F4 'half 0.8)     ;; extends across the barline into measure 2 *[needs: GAP-2]*
(note/place-at 6 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
(note/place-at 7 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
```

`[VISUAL: Two measures in 4/4. A half note begins on beat 4 of measure 1 and is tied (curved line) to a quarter note on beat 1 of measure 2, creating a combined duration of three beats.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-2 tie glyph is added, render the tie arc; note-sprite holds across the barline -->

---


### Chapter Finale: A rhythm that keeps time (composite march in 4/4)

This finale combines everything: steady tempo, clear meter, varied subdivisions, rests, accents, and two independent rhythmic voices. It is a *composite march* — melody in quarters and eighths, bass in steady quarters, a snare pattern on the backbeats.

```scheme
;; Finale: A composite 4/4 march (four measures)
(transport/tempo 112)

;; Bass drum: steady quarters on all four beats
(define (bass-measure start)
  (note/place-at start 'C2 'quarter 0.85)
  (note/place-at (+ start 1) 'C2 'quarter 0.85)
  (note/place-at (+ start 2) 'C2 'quarter 0.85)
  (note/place-at (+ start 3) 'C2 'quarter 0.85))

;; Snare: backbeats (beats 2 and 4)
(define (snare-measure start)
  (note/place-at (+ start 1) 'D3 'quarter 0.9)
  (note/place-at (+ start 3) 'D3 'quarter 0.9))

;; Melody: mixed quarters and eighths
(define (melody-measure-1 start)
  (note/place-at start 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/place-at (+ start 1) 'A4 'eighth 0.75)
  (note/place-at (+ start 1.5) 'B4 'eighth 0.75)
  (note/place-at (+ start 2) 'C5 'quarter 0.85)
  (note/place-at (+ start 3) 'B4 'quarter 0.8))

(define (melody-measure-2 start)
  (note/place-at start 'A4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/place-at (+ start 1) 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/place-at (+ start 2) 'F4 'half 0.75))

;; Assemble four measures
(bass-measure 1)
(snare-measure 1)
(melody-measure-1 1)

(bass-measure 5)
(snare-measure 5)
(melody-measure-2 5)

(bass-measure 9)
(snare-measure 9)
(melody-measure-1 9)

(bass-measure 13)
(snare-measure 13)
(melody-measure-2 13)
```

`[VISUAL: A four-measure grand staff in 4/4 time. Top staff (treble clef): melody with quarters and eighths. Bottom staff (bass clef): steady quarter notes (bass) with snare hits notated on a separate line or as cross-noteheads on beats 2 and 4 of each measure. Tempo marking ♩ = 112. Time signature 4/4. Barlines every four beats. All note-sprites bob in sync with the 112 BPM pulse; melody sprites bob faster during eighth-note runs, bass sprites maintain a steady quarter-note pulse, snare sprites flash/accent on beats 2 and 4.]`

<!-- BUILD: render four-measure grand staff with melody, bass, and snare notation; tempo and time signature glyphs; all note-sprites animated at correct rates and synchronized to the beat -->

This is a rhythm that keeps time — a march that drives forward, each voice locked to the grid, each subdivision clear, each accent intentional. The beat is the anchor. Everything else dances around it, but never drifts.

---


---

## Notes and Additional Considerations from r2 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r2 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### The beat is the grid

A **beat** is the smallest regular pulse you count. One beat. Two beats. Three beats. Four.

When you clap along to a song, you are clapping on beats. When a conductor waves a baton, each wave marks a beat. A beat is the unit of musical time.

```scheme
;; A single beat, as a quarter note on middle C
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
```

`[VISUAL: A quarter note on the staff, alone. The note-sprite bobs once, in time.]`

<!-- BUILD: render one quarter note on a treble staff, centered; animate the note-sprite with one beat-synced bob -->

That program schedules a note to sound for one beat. The duration `'quarter` means \"this note lasts one beat.\" The beat itself is abstract — it is not a number of seconds until we set a **tempo**.

---


### Tempo: how fast is a beat?

Tempo is the speed of the beat, measured in **beats per minute (BPM)**. A march might be 120 BPM — 120 beats in one minute, or two beats per second. A waltz might be 90 BPM. A dirge might be 60.

The transport knows the tempo, and every note's duration is calculated from it.

```scheme
;; Set the tempo to 120 BPM and play four quarter notes
(transport/tempo 120)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 64)
```

At 120 BPM, one beat is 0.5 seconds. Four beats take two seconds.

Now change the tempo:

```scheme
;; The same four notes, but slower
(transport/tempo 60)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 64)
```

At 60 BPM, one beat is one second. Four beats take four seconds. The notes are the same, the rhythm is the same, but the *speed* is different.

`[VISUAL: Two staves side-by-side. The first labeled \"120 BPM\", the second \"60 BPM\". Both show four quarter notes ascending C-D-E-F. The second staff's note-sprites bob half as fast.]`

<!-- BUILD: render two 4-note staves side-by-side with tempo labels; sync note-sprite bob rate to tempo -->

---


### Measures: grouping beats

Beats alone make a grid, but they do not make a **shape**. A shape comes from grouping beats into **measures** (also called bars). A measure is a container: it holds a fixed number of beats, and that number is the **time signature**.

**4/4 time** (four-four) means \"four beats per measure, and the quarter note gets one beat.\" Most marches, most pop songs, and most of what you will write for the next few chapters live in 4/4.

```scheme
;; A simple 4/4 measure: four quarter notes
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
```

That is one measure of 4/4. The measure is not a Scheme form — it is a conceptual grouping. The notes above fill one measure because they total four beats.

`[VISUAL: One measure of 4/4 on a staff, with a time signature at the start and a barline at the end. Four quarter notes, all middle C.]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 4/4 measure with time signature glyph (4 over 4) at the left, four quarter notes, barline at the right -->

---


### Different time signatures

**3/4 time** (three-four) means \"three beats per measure.\" This is waltz time. ONE-two-three, ONE-two-three.

```scheme
;; A waltz measure in 3/4
(transport/tempo 90)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 72)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 48)
(note/strike 67 'quarter 48)
```

One measure: three beats. The first beat is accented (velocity 72), the second and third lighter (velocity 48). That accent pattern is what makes it feel like a waltz.

`[VISUAL: One measure of 3/4. Time signature 3/4, three quarter notes C-E-G, the first note slightly larger (louder).]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 3/4 measure with three quarter notes, first note rendered slightly bolder to indicate accent -->

**2/4 time** is duple meter: ONE-two, ONE-two. A march.

```scheme
;; A 2/4 march measure
(transport/tempo 120)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 80)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)
```

Two beats. Strong-weak. The measure ends after the second beat.

`[VISUAL: One measure of 2/4. Time signature 2/4, two quarter notes C-D, first note accented.]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 2/4 measure with two quarter notes, first accented -->

---


### Placing notes at specific beats

So far, every note has started immediately after the previous note ends. But sometimes you want to place a note *at a specific beat* in the measure. The `base/at-beat` form does this.

```scheme
;; Place notes at beats 0, 2, and 3 in a 4/4 measure
(transport/tempo 100)
(base/at-beat 0 (note/strike 60 'quarter 64))
(base/at-beat 2 (note/strike 64 'quarter 64))
(base/at-beat 3 (note/strike 67 'quarter 64))
```

Beat 0 is the downbeat (the first beat of the measure). Beat 2 is the third beat (counting from zero). Beat 3 is the fourth beat. This measure has a rest on beat 1 because no note was placed there.

`[VISUAL: A 4/4 staff with notes on beats 0, 2, and 3. Beat 1 shows a quarter rest.]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 4/4 measure with notes on beats 0, 2, 3 and a quarter rest on beat 1 -->

---


### Spanning multiple measures

A piece is many measures. You can write them out sequentially, or you can use `base/land-on-downbeat` to snap the transport to the start of the next measure.

```scheme
;; Two measures of 4/4
(transport/tempo 120)

;; Measure 1
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 64)

;; Measure 2
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 67 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)
```

The first measure ascends C-D-E-F. The call to `base/land-on-downbeat` ensures the second measure starts exactly on the next downbeat, even if the first measure's notes did not perfectly fill four beats. The second measure descends G-F-E-D.

`[VISUAL: Two 4/4 measures on one staff, separated by a barline. First measure: C-D-E-F ascending. Second measure: G-F-E-D descending.]`

<!-- BUILD: render two 4/4 measures on one staff with a barline between them -->

---


### Rests are rhythm too

A **rest** is silence, but it is not the absence of rhythm — it is rhythm made of silence. Rests occupy beats just like notes do.

```scheme
;; A measure with rests
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
;; (a quarter rest here — no sound, but one beat passes)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 64)
;; (another quarter rest)
```

You do not write rests as Scheme forms (there is no `(rest 'quarter)`), but you **account for them** by placing notes at the beats where sound should occur, and letting the other beats remain silent.

If you want explicit rests for visual clarity or to align with a staff rendering:

```scheme
;; A 4/4 measure: note, rest, note, rest
(transport/tempo 100)
(base/at-beat 0 (note/strike 60 'quarter 64))
(base/at-beat 2 (note/strike 64 'quarter 64))
```

`[VISUAL: A 4/4 measure with notes on beats 0 and 2, quarter rests on beats 1 and 3.]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 4/4 measure with quarter notes on beats 0 and 2, quarter rest glyphs on beats 1 and 3 -->

---


### A simple march in 2/4

A march is duple meter, strong-weak, strong-weak. Let us write four measures.

```scheme
;; A four-measure march in 2/4
(transport/tempo 120)

;; Measure 1
(note/strike 60 'quarter 80)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)

;; Measure 2
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 80)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)

;; Measure 3
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 80)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 64)

;; Measure 4
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 80)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 64)
```

Each measure has two quarter notes. The first beat of each measure is louder (velocity 80), the second softer (velocity 64). The march ascends C-C, D-D, E-E, F-F.

`[VISUAL: Four measures of 2/4, each with two quarter notes, first note of each measure accented. Notes ascend by step.]`

<!-- BUILD: render four 2/4 measures with ascending pairs of quarter notes, downbeats accented -->

---


### A waltz in 3/4

A waltz is triple meter: ONE-two-three, ONE-two-three. The first beat is the downbeat, strong. The second and third beats are lighter.

```scheme
;; A four-measure waltz in 3/4
(transport/tempo 90)

;; Measure 1: C-E-G
(note/strike 60 'quarter 72)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 48)
(note/strike 67 'quarter 48)

;; Measure 2: G-E-C
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 67 'quarter 72)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 48)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 48)

;; Measure 3: F-A-C
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 72)
(note/strike 69 'quarter 48)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 48)

;; Measure 4: C-A-F
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 72)
(note/strike 69 'quarter 48)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 48)
```

Each measure has three beats. The first beat of each measure is accented. The harmony outlines tonic and subdominant arpeggios.

`[VISUAL: Four measures of 3/4, each with three quarter notes, first note of each measure accented. The melody traces arpeggios.]`

<!-- BUILD: render four 3/4 measures with three quarter notes each, downbeats accented, notes forming arpeggios -->

