### Syncopation: accenting the off-beat

**Syncopation** is when you accent a beat (or part of a beat) that is normally weak. It disrupts the expected strong-weak pattern and creates rhythmic surprise.

```scheme
;; A syncopated 4/4 measure
(transport/tempo 100)
(base/at-beat 0 (note/strike 60 'quarter 48))   ;; downbeat, soft
(base/at-beat 1.5 (note/strike 64 'eighth 80))  ;; off-beat, loud
(base/at-beat 2 (note/strike 67 'quarter 48))   ;; beat 3, soft
(base/at-beat 3.5 (note/strike 64 'eighth 80))  ;; off-beat, loud
```

Beats 1.5 and 3.5 are the \"and\" of beats 2 and 4 — the spaces *between* the main beats. By making those notes louder, you shift the accent away from the downbeat.

`[VISUAL: A 4/4 measure with quarter notes on beats 1 and 3 (softer), and eighth notes on the off-beats (louder, visually accented).]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 4/4 measure with notes on beats 0, 1.5, 2, 3.5; off-beat notes accented -->

---


### A driving syncopated rhythm in 4/4

Syncopation is the backbone of funk, jazz, and Latin music. Here is a two-measure groove:

```scheme
;; A syncopated two-measure groove
(transport/tempo 110)

;; Measure 1
(base/at-beat 0 (note/strike 60 'quarter 72))
(base/at-beat 1.5 (note/strike 64 'eighth 80))
(base/at-beat 2 (note/strike 60 'quarter 64))
(base/at-beat 3.5 (note/strike 64 'eighth 80))

;; Measure 2
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(base/at-beat 0 (note/strike 60 'quarter 72))
(base/at-beat 1 (note/strike 62 'quarter 64))
(base/at-beat 2.5 (note/strike 64 'eighth 80))
(base/at-beat 3 (note/strike 67 'quarter 64))
```

The off-beat accents (beats 1.5, 3.5, 2.5) pull against the downbeat. The rhythm grooves.

`[VISUAL: Two 4/4 measures with notes on various beats and off-beats, off-beat notes accented.]`

<!-- BUILD: render two 4/4 measures with on-beat and off-beat notes, off-beats visually accented -->

