### Triplets: dividing the beat into three *[needs: GAP-1]*

A **triplet** divides one beat into three equal parts. In 4/4, one beat is normally divided into two eighth notes. A triplet divides it into three.

```scheme
;; A 4/4 measure with quarter-note triplets *[needs: GAP-1]*
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/strike 60 'triplet 64)
(note/strike 62 'triplet 64)
(note/strike 64 'triplet 64)
;; (that was one beat — three triplet notes)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 67 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 69 'quarter 64)
```

The first beat has three triplet notes. The remaining three beats are normal quarter notes.

`[VISUAL: A 4/4 measure. The first beat has three notes under a triplet bracket. The next three beats are quarter notes.]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 4/4 measure with triplet notation on beat 1, three quarter notes on beats 2-4 (awaits GAP-1: triplet duration support) -->

Triplets are not yet in the engine — this is GAP-1. When GAP-1 closes, you will be able to use `'triplet` (and other tuplets) as durations.

---


### Sixteenth notes: four per beat

A **sixteenth note** lasts one-quarter of a beat. Four sixteenth notes fit in one quarter note.

```scheme
;; A 4/4 measure with a burst of sixteenth notes
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 64 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 65 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 67 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 69 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 67 'quarter 64)
```

Beats 1 and 2 are quarter notes. Beat 3 is four sixteenth notes (one beat total). Beat 4 is a quarter note.

`[VISUAL: A 4/4 measure: two quarter notes, four beamed sixteenth notes, one quarter note.]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 4/4 measure with two quarters, four beamed sixteenths, one quarter -->

---


### A running sixteenth-note pattern

Sixteenth notes can create rapid, driving motion.

```scheme
;; A two-measure pattern built from sixteenth-note runs
(transport/tempo 100)

;; Measure 1: four beats of sixteenth notes
(note/strike 60 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 62 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 64 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 65 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 67 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 65 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 64 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 62 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 60 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 62 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 64 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 65 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 67 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 69 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 71 'sixteenth 64)
(note/strike 72 'sixteenth 64)

;; Measure 2: resolve to a half note
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 60 'half 72)
```

Measure 1 is sixteen sixteenth notes — a continuous run. Measure 2 resolves to a sustained half note.

`[VISUAL: Two 4/4 measures. The first is densely filled with beamed sixteenth notes. The second has a half note on beats 1-2, then rests.]`

