### A waltz with accompaniment

Let us write a waltz with a bass note on beat 1 and chords on beats 2 and 3.

```scheme
;; A four-measure 3/4 waltz with bass and chords
(transport/tempo 90)

(define (waltz-measure bass chord1 chord2)
  (base/at-beat 0 (note/strike bass 'quarter 72))        ;; bass on beat 1
  (base/at-beat 1 (note/strike chord1 'quarter 48))      ;; chord on beat 2
  (base/at-beat 2 (note/strike chord2 'quarter 48)))     ;; chord on beat 3

;; Measure 1: C bass, E and G chords
(waltz-measure 48 64 67)

;; Measure 2: G bass, B and D chords
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(waltz-measure 55 71 62)

;; Measure 3: F bass, A and C chords
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(waltz-measure 53 69 60)

;; Measure 4: C bass, E and G chords
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(waltz-measure 48 64 67)
```

Each measure has three beats. Beat 1 is a low bass note (one octave below middle C). Beats 2 and 3 are chord tones in the middle register. The pattern is: bass, chord, chord.

`[VISUAL: Four 3/4 measures on two staves. Bottom staff: bass notes on beat 1. Top staff: chord tones on beats 2 and 3.]`

