### Counting in 6/8: compound meter

**6/8 time** has six eighth notes per measure, but they are grouped in two sets of three. You count it \"ONE-two-three, TWO-two-three\" — not \"one, two, three, four, five, six.\" It is a **compound duple meter**: two main beats, each subdivided into three.

```scheme
;; A 6/8 measure
(transport/tempo 80)
(note/strike 60 'eighth 72)  ;; ONE
(note/strike 62 'eighth 48)  ;; two
(note/strike 64 'eighth 48)  ;; three
(note/strike 65 'eighth 72)  ;; TWO
(note/strike 64 'eighth 48)  ;; two
(note/strike 62 'eighth 48)  ;; three
```

The first and fourth eighth notes are accented (velocity 72). That creates the two main beats.

`[VISUAL: A 6/8 measure with six eighth notes. Notes 1 and 4 are accented.]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 6/8 measure with six eighth notes, first and fourth notes accented -->

---


### A lilting 6/8 melody

6/8 is common in folk music and lullabies. It has a rocking, lilting feel.

```scheme
;; A four-measure 6/8 melody
(transport/tempo 80)

;; Measure 1
(note/strike 60 'eighth 72)
(note/strike 62 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 64 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 65 'eighth 72)
(note/strike 64 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 62 'eighth 48)

;; Measure 2
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 60 'eighth 72)
(note/strike 64 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 67 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 65 'eighth 72)
(note/strike 64 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 62 'eighth 48)

;; Measure 3
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 67 'eighth 72)
(note/strike 65 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 64 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 62 'eighth 72)
(note/strike 60 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 62 'eighth 48)

;; Measure 4
(base/land-on-downbeat)
(note/strike 60 'eighth 72)
(note/strike 62 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 64 'eighth 48)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 72) ;; dotted quarter = 3 eighths
```

The final measure ends with a dotted quarter note — three eighth notes' worth of time — which fills beats 4-5-6.

`[VISUAL: Four 6/8 measures with lilting eighth-note melodies, last measure ending with a dotted quarter note.]`

<!-- BUILD: render four 6/8 measures with eighth-note patterns, last measure ending with a dotted quarter note -->

