### Accelerando: speeding up over time

An **accelerando** is a gradual increase in tempo. The music gets faster.

The transport does not yet have a built-in accelerando form, but you can approximate it by changing the tempo between measures.

```scheme
;; A four-measure pattern that accelerates
(transport/tempo 80)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 64)

(base/land-on-downbeat)
(transport/tempo 90)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 64)

(base/land-on-downbeat)
(transport/tempo 100)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 64)

(base/land-on-downbeat)
(transport/tempo 110)
(note/strike 60 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 62 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 64 'quarter 64)
(note/strike 65 'quarter 64)
```

Each measure is the same melody (C-D-E-F), but the tempo increases from 80 to 90 to 100 to 110. The music speeds up.

`[VISUAL: Four 4/4 measures on one staff. Tempo markings above each measure: \"♩=80\", \"♩=90\", \"♩=100\", \"♩=110\".]`

<!-- BUILD: render four 4/4 measures with tempo markings above each -->

