### A rhythm that accelerates within the measure

Instead of changing tempo between measures, let us change the *spacing* of notes within a measure to create an accelerating feel.

```scheme
;; A measure where notes get closer together (accelerating feel)
(transport/tempo 100)
(base/at-beat 0 (note/strike 60 'eighth 64))
(base/at-beat 0.5 (note/strike 62 'eighth 64))
(base/at-beat 0.875 (note/strike 64 'eighth 64))  ;; closer
(base/at-beat 1.125 (note/strike 65 'eighth 64))  ;; even closer
(base/at-beat 1.3125 (note/strike 67 'eighth 64)) ;; very close
```

The first two notes are 0.5 beats apart. Then the spacing shrinks: 0.375, 0.25, 0.1875. The notes rush together.

`[VISUAL: A 4/4 measure with five notes, spaced progressively closer together from left to right.]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 4/4 measure with notes spaced progressively closer to show internal accelerando -->

---


### A rhythm that decelerates within the measure

The opposite: notes that start close together and spread out.

```scheme
;; A measure where notes get farther apart (decelerating feel)
(transport/tempo 100)
(base/at-beat 0 (note/strike 60 'eighth 64))
(base/at-beat 0.25 (note/strike 62 'eighth 64))   ;; close
(base/at-beat 0.625 (note/strike 64 'eighth 64))  ;; wider
(base/at-beat 1.25 (note/strike 65 'eighth 64))   ;; wider still
(base/at-beat 2.25 (note/strike 67 'eighth 64))   ;; very wide
```

The spacing grows: 0.25, 0.375, 0.625, 1.0. The rhythm slows down within the measure.

`[VISUAL: A 4/4 measure with five notes, spaced progressively farther apart from left to right.]`

<!-- BUILD: render a 4/4 measure with notes spaced progressively wider to show internal ritardando -->

